{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_chapel_ver01/data/sn87055779/00517017656/1923122101/0289.xml":{"full_text":"i BUSINESS HEADS\nPREDICT GOLDEN\nit YEAR FOR 1924\nIff:,\nContinued Improvement Fore\ncast by Leaders of Finance\nWorld.\n(Copyright, 1928, By I. N. S.)\nNEW YORK, Dec. 20.\u2014America\nj faces one of Its greatest post-war\nbusiness years In. 1924. A majority\nof business leaders look for \u201ccon\ntinued Improvement*' over 1928, re\ngarded generally as a good year. The\nmost pessimistic prediction looks to\nthe new year with \"conservative op\ntimism.\"\nThis Is the concensus compiled by\nInternational News Service from\nbankers, merchants and manufac\nturers from coast to coast. Busi\nness barometers cited In proof of the\ni hopeful view are the condition of\nstocks, the building boom, improve\nment\u00bb> and additions to railroad\ni equipment. Increased savings de\nposits, a rush for life insurance,\nound employment conditions and the\nvastly Improved condition of the\nAmerican farmer.\nReliable Barometer.\nThe steel industry la conceded to\nbe the most reliable \"business bar\nometer.'l\nElbert H. Gary, chairman of the.\nboard of directors of the United\nStates Steel corporation, found buai\nness good In 1928.\n\u201cI look for It to be even better In\n1924,\u201d hs said. \u201cThere are no lim\nits to the possibility of Industry and\nbusiness In the United States. Amer\nican prosperity has by no means\ntouched the high water mark.\u201d\nSimilar Note.\nA similar note Is sounded by\nJames H. Farrell, president of the\nUnited States Steel corporation, who\nj believes \u201cAmerica is over-emphaslz- j\nlng the troubles of Europe.\u201d\n\u201cSo far as America is concerned,\u201d\nhe said, \u201cthere has been a constant-\nly Improving situation in business\n\\f and I look for this to continue.\u201d\nH. T. Parson, of New York,\n\"America\u2019s merchant prince,\u201d head j\nof a chai nof five and ten cent stores, j\nsees a great stimulus for business in j\nI tax reduction legislation and regards\nsuch action by congress as inevit\nable.\nAdded Resource.\ninrougn seiuemem ui me rep\narations question, an added re\nsource for American business will be\nassured,\" he adds.\nf Daniel J. Willard, president of the\nBaltimore Ohio railroad, is \"high\nly encouraged\" by 1924 prospects for\nthe railroads. He does not, however,\nexpect freight tonnage to equal that\nof 1923\u2014the record of American\ntransportation history.\n\u201cWe can hardly expect the coun\ntry to do a great export business\nWhile present disturbed conditions in\nEurope continue,' 'he said.\nThomas E. Wilson, Chicago pack\nt er said: \u201cWe will have prosperity in\n1924. Good business will prevail\nprovided business men give it an op\nportunity and continue to sound an\noptimistic note.\"\n\u201cRetail trade for 1924 will great\nly exceed that of 1923, which was\n20 to 26 per cent better than in\n1922,\u201d.declared Thomas May, of Dos\nm\ny Hark to Mr. Dempsey*s Confession\nJ nn i i jgiijy 11 _ I\n(By Padflc Atlantic)\nAdmitting to woman reporter (above), Jack Dempsey, upon arrival\nin New York, said he was \u201cwoman-proof!\u201d BUT\u2014 and Jack said\u2014\n\"A sweet, good woman with brains and intelligence will some day\nbe my wife.\u201d The Mauler presented a rose to his interviewer.\nAngeles .president of the May de\npartment stores.\n\u201cLos Angeles' building record of\n$115,000,000 in 1923 will be eclipsed\nin 1924,\" promises Sylvester Weaver,\nformer president of the Chamber of\nCommerce.\nSec\u2019y of Commerce Hoover said:\n\"We have never had a cleaner sit\nuation than at present, and never\nhave we had a sounder business sit\nuation than at present. We have\nmore employment at higher real\nwages tluin ever before, more buying\npower tnan in a decade, and a\nlarger demand for homes and an\nextensive buying of building ma\nterials.\"\nBig Bank Profits.\nHenry G. Dawes, comptroller of\nthe currency, said: \u201cIn the past year\nprofits of national banks were $203,\n600,000, notwithstanding the writing\noff of $160,000,000 in losses. Divi\ndends of $179,000,000 yfere paid,\nsetting a record in the history of\nnational banks. This reflects the\neminently satisfactory condition of\nnational banks and forecasts tl/eir\nability to fully meet the demands of\n1924. National banks 'reflect the\nnational business outlook.\"\n\u201cBusiness interests of the Pacific\ncoast have every reason to view the\nadvent of 1924 with conservative op\ntimism,\" says Herbert Fleischaker,\nSari Francisco banker. \u201cCommodity\nprices are firm; there is no' unem\nployment problem: our population is\nsteadily increasing and our buying\npower apparently well stabilized.\u201d\nWilliam Wrigley, Chicago gum\nmanufacturer and baseball magnate\nIs a \u201cbull on the business outlook.\u201d\nHe expects 1924 to be a \u201cworld beat\ner in a business sense.\"\ns Congress Can Help.\nCongress can aid the good businesa\nprospects, according to Festus J.\nWad$, St. Louis merchant, by \u201cwise\naction in some lines and wise inac\ntion in others.\u201d He suggests tax re\nductions and wants the transporta\ntion act and the federal reserve sys\ntem \u201clet alone.\"\nThe farmers\u2019 opinion Is expressed\nby Hortier Miller, of Dea Molnes.\npresident of the Iowa National bank.\n\u201cThe outlook for 1924 la favor\nable.\" he says. \u201cMerchants are buy\ning sparingly and there is no infla\ntion. That augurs well for prosper\nity.\u201d y\nEdgard Senaenich, of Portland,\npresident of the Oregon Bankers\u2019\nAssn., looks forward to an \u201ceven\nmore prosperous 1924\u201d for Oregon,\nwhich \"experienced the most satis\nfactory business year of its history\nin 1923.\u201d\n\u201cThe outlook for the United\nStates was never clearer,\u201d declares\nClarence W. Barron, of Boston, pub\nlisher of business organs. \u201cWe hold\nthe central position in the world of\nlab9r, the source of wealth in gold,\nthe source of credit and Interest, al\nso the source of prosperity.\"\nIncreased Market.\nNew England, furnishing an In\ncreased market, will aid the textile\nindustry, according to Frederick K.\nRupprecht, chairman of the exec\nutive committee of the Consolidated\nTextile Coxp.\n\"Conditions are fundamentally\ngood,\u201d he said.\nScores of other statements are of\na like tone. There is unanimity in\nthe feehng that the fact that 1924 is\na presidential year will no* interfere\nwith the steady march ot business\nand industrial progress.\nEGG PRICES DROP\nIN KANSAS CITY\nBy United Press:\nKANSAS CITY, Mo., Dec. /20\u2014\nEggs sold for 33 cents a dozen In\nKansas City today, after declining\n15 cents a dozen within the last two\nweeks. Prices dropped one cent to\nday, making a total of five cents\nwithin three \u00ae&ys. At 33 cents, eggs\nare nine cents under the price for\nthis time last year.\nJURYMEN CONVICT\nFORMER MANAGER\nFOR DOLLINGS\nDwight Harrison to File Mo\ntion for New Trial in\nColumbus.\nBy International News Service:\nCOLUMBUS, O., Dec. 20\u2014A mo\n\ntion for a new trial was to be filed\ntoday by Dwight Harrison, forme;\ngeneral manager of the defunct R\nL. Dolllngs Co., of Ohio, found guil\nty by a jury in common plena coin\nlast night of false representation ii\nthe sale of stock of the Phoenix\nPortland Cement Co., of Ohio, a\nDollings subsidiary.\nThe verdict came after three\nhours\u2019 deliberation, at the close o:\nthe longest trial ever held in the\nFranklin county criminal cour'\nHarrison accepted the verdict calm\nly and said that It was what he ha\nexpected.\nThe case grew out of the eras!\nand receivership of the Dollings Co\nand its numerous subsidiaries with\nresultant loss estimated at fron\n$25,000,000 to $70,000,000 to thou-\nsands of small investors in Ohio ami\nother states.\nDEALINGS STUDDED\nBy United Press:\nINDIANAPOLIS, Dec. 20.\u2014Involv\ned financial dealings between thi\nR. L. Dollies Co., of Indiana, am\nits two subsidiaries, the Internation\nal Note and Mortgage Co., of Indi\nanapolis. and the Western Drop\nForge Co., of Marion, are under con\nsideration by Superior Judge Linn D\nHay, today.\nBert S. McBride, receiver for the\nDollings and International Note an\nMortgage Cos., has asked the Judg\nto approve a reorganization plan fo\nthe Marion concern, which owes h\ntwo charges approximately $400,00\nJudge Hay said lie would annoum\nhis decision as to whether he woui\napprove the receiver\u2019s plans Frida;\nIf the Marion company is reo,\nganized, McBride isaid, his two coir\npanies stand a better chance of rea\nizing something on their debts.\nPayment in full of all claim\nthrough the issuance of new secur.\nties will be effected if the reorgan;\nzation plan is approved, McBrid\nsaid. Preferred stock hr the ne\ncompany would be issued to th\nstockholders of the Western Dro\nForge Co., in proportion to th\namount of stock now held in th\ndefunct concern by each stockhdh\ner, it is understood.\nMcBride estimated liabilities of th\nMarion Co., at about $400,000.\nNavy Program for Lan\nPurchase Is Prebente\nBy International News Service:\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 20-vTi\nnavy\u2019s program for. the purchase\nland on the Pacific and Atlarn.\ncoasts for the development of ehor>\nestablishments and the sale of lane\nno longer needed was presented for\ncongressional approval today in a\nbill introduced by Rep. Britten, Re\npublican, of Illinois, a member o?\nthe house naval affairs committee.\nThousands Have Taken Advantage\nAFFORDED BY FIRE SALE\nOF1\n$80,000 Worth of Men\u2019s Clothing\nOvercoats, Suits, Hats, Caps and Furnishings, also Boys\u2019 Suits, Over\ncoats, Hats and Caps\nDamaged By The Smoke\nOtherwise no discolorations whatsoever\n_\nBecause of Astonishingly Low Prices\nOn the highest grade Merchandise made by Hirsch Wickwire, Ard\nmore Clothes, Adler, Collegian, and many other such well known\nlines that people expect to find Merchandise badly damaged. But\nwe assure you that there is no other dama